Project 2

Analysing the impact of studying online vs on campus on a university student’s academic performance.

480434182, 480385183, 510615460, 480514277, 500377815

University of Sydney | 8 October 2021


1 Executive Summary

  • This report aims to investigate how studying online affects the academic performance of university students.
  • The main discovery was that although students dedicated more time to uni work when studying remotely they preferred the academic experience on campus and received higher grades when attending classes in-person.


2 Full Report

2.1.1 Summary:

2.1.1.1 Source

  • The data was obtained from an online Google Forms survey conducted from 16/09/2021 to 19/04/2021.

2.1.1.2 Structure:

  • Each row represents an individual response, with 35 responses recorded in total.
  • Each column displays a survey question, with 10 variables in total (6 qualitative and 4 quantitative).

2.1.1.3 Limitations:

  • There are several limitations that stem from selection bias:
    • Students with no exposure to on campus study were not taken into consideration
    • University students were only targeted and the majority of them were third year(37%).
    • The survey was primarily distributed to University of Sydney students.
    • Thus, the results obtained from this study cannot be generalised to all students.
  • Students were not asked to specify the unit that they received their highest grade, which doesn’t account for differences in difficulty between units-of-study, degrees and attending university.
  • This observational study only establishes associations between variables but not causation.
  • Consent bias could have also confounded our results as students had the choice to partake in the survey

2.1.1.4 Assumptions

  • That respondents would answer truthfully in regards to achieved grades.
  • That everyone has the same definition of studying.
  • That all respondents provided reliable averages for hours studying per week.

2.1.1.5 Data Cleaning

  • The responses made by students who didn’t have exposure to on-campus study were removed from the data set.
  • Removed one result that was submitted prior to finalizing the survey.
  • Changed the type of responses from questions to variables.

2.2 Research Question(s)

2.2.1 Does online study impact a student’s academic performance?

library(gridExtra)
library(ggplot2)

cc = ggplot(survey, aes(highestAve_cc)) + geom_histogram(breaks=seq(65, 100, by=5), col="black", fill="lightcoral") + labs(title="Highest Average Marks of Students Studying On-Campus", x="Highest Average Mark", y="Number of Students") + xlim(c(65,100)) + ylim(c(0,12))

re = ggplot(survey, aes(highestAve_re)) + geom_histogram(breaks=seq(65, 100, by=5), col="black", fill="rosybrown3") + labs(title="Highest Average Marks of Students Studying Remotely", x="Highest Average Mark", y="Number of Students") + xlim(c(65,100)) + ylim(c(0,12))

grid.arrange(cc, re, nrow = 2)

mean(survey$highestAve_cc)
## [1] 84.94286
mean(survey$highestAve_re)
## [1] 83.08571

2.2.1.1 Analysis

  • The mean average mark achieved by students on-campus was about 1.86% higher than those who studied remotely.
  • As expected, students achieved higher marks whilst studying and attending classes on-campus compared to when studying/attending classes online.
  • Thus, online study does have an impact on academic achievements as it appears to limit a student’s ability to achieve the higher marks they received whilst studying/attending classes on-campus.

2.2.2 Does studying online vs on campus impact the amount of hours studied per week?

library(ggplot2)

ggplot(survey, aes(y=currentyear, x=hoursSpentStudying_cc, fill=currentyear)) + geom_boxplot() + labs(y= "Current Year", x = "Hours Spent Studying in a Week (On-Campus)") + scale_fill_brewer(palette="PuBu")+ scale_x_continuous(n.breaks = 8) 

ggplot(survey, aes(y=currentyear, x=hoursSpentStudiying_re, fill=currentyear)) + geom_boxplot() + labs(y= "Current Year", x = "Hours Spent Studying in a Week (Remote)") + scale_fill_brewer(palette="PuBu") + scale_x_continuous(n.breaks = 8)

2.2.2.1 Analysis

  • Overall, students tend to spend slightly more time studying when they attend university remotely.
  • Considering our previous finding that on-campus study appears to be associated with higher grades, the efficacy of online study may be lower than that of on-campus study. This is because the longer study hours associated with remote study does not appear to equate to higher grades. Thus, further research into other possible factors that may reduce the efficacy of online study is needed.
  • In the on-campus boxplot, there is a point located outside the whiskers of the plot which indicates that there is one outlier while the remote boxplot do not have any outliers
  • As expected, first and second year students dedicated the most time to studying. This is perhaps due to their unfamiliarity with how to manage their university workload in an efficient manner or their eagerness to put more time into achieving high grades.

2.2.3 Does the number of hours spent studying online vs on campus affect the marks received by students?

ggplot(survey, aes(y=highestAve_cc, x=hoursSpentStudying_cc)) + geom_point(aes(colour = currentyear)) + labs(y= "Highest Average Mark", x = "Hours Spent Studying in a Week (On-Campus)") + ggtitle("Number of hours spent studying and average mark") + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se=F, color = "darkslategray") + scale_x_continuous(n.breaks = 10) +scale_y_continuous(n.breaks = 10) + theme(legend.position = "bottom") 
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

l = lm(survey$highestAve_cc ~ survey$hoursSpentStudying_cc)

ggplot(survey, aes(y=l$residuals, x=hoursSpentStudying_cc)) + geom_point() + geom_hline(yintercept=0, colour = "red", size = 1) + ylab("Residuals") + xlab("Hours Spent Studying in a Week (On-Campus)") + scale_x_continuous(n.breaks = 10) + scale_y_continuous(n.breaks = 10) + theme(legend.position = "top")

cor(survey$highestAve_cc, survey$hoursSpentStudying_cc)
## [1] 0.09660252
lm(survey$highestAve_cc ~ survey$hoursSpentStudying_cc)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = survey$highestAve_cc ~ survey$hoursSpentStudying_cc)
## 
## Coefficients:
##                  (Intercept)  survey$hoursSpentStudying_cc  
##                     83.59574                       0.09227
model = lm(survey$highestAve_cc ~ survey$hoursSpentStudying_cc)
qqnorm(survey$hoursSpentStudying_cc, ylab = "Standardized Residuals")
qqline(survey$hoursSpentStudying_cc)

2.2.3.1 Analysis

  • There appears to be a weak positive correlation between the number of hours spent studying per-week and academic performance during on-campus semesters.
  • However, there is a slightly stronger positive correlation between the number of hours spent studying per week and academic performance during semesters with predominantly online delivery.
  • The heteroscedasticity of the residual plots indicates that linear regression may not be an appropriate model.

2.2.4 Do students believe that studying on campus would improve their academic performance?

library(ggplot2)

#Add order of current years 
order_marks = ordered(survey$perceivedMarkChange,levels = c("0 - 20 % lower", "20-40% lower","0 - 20 % higher", "20-40% higher", "40-60% higher", "Greater than 60% higher"))

ggplot(survey, aes(x=factor(order_marks)), group = interaction(order_marks, currentyear)) + geom_bar(aes(fill=currentyear)) + ylab("Number of Students") + xlab("Perceived Mark Change") + ggtitle("Students' perceived change in marks if on-campus study was available") + scale_fill_brewer(palette="Accent") +
scale_y_continuous(n.breaks = 10) + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=45, hjust=1))  

order_preference = ordered(survey$ccVSre,levels = c("Strongly prefer on-campus", "Prefer on-campus","Indifferent", "Prefer online", "Strongly prefer online"))

ggplot(survey, aes(x=factor(order_preference)), group = interaction(order_preference, currentyear))+ geom_bar(aes(fill=currentyear)) + ylab("Number of Students") + xlab("Preference") + ggtitle("Preference for studying online or on-campus based on academic experience") + scale_fill_brewer(palette="Accent") + scale_y_continuous(n.breaks = 10) + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=45, hjust=1, size = 8))

2.2.4.1 Analysis

  • The majority of students (66%) believe that they would receive higher grades if they could study on-campus instead of studying online during the current semester.
  • 60% of the students prefer studying on campus whilst only 11% were indifferent to the idea and 29% preferred online study.
  • Thus as anticipated, the majority of students believe that studying on-campus would improve their academic performance and they also prefer the overall academic experience that on-campus study provides.

3 Articles

Our findings aligned with research conducted on students conducting study online. Disconnect between student/lecturer, internet issues and poor allotment of lecture time were all factors in dissatisfaction of online study (Khalil, R. et al.(2020)) . This leads to students completing less lectures/work, which directly correlates with lower results (Williams, A., Birch, E., & Hancock, P. (2012))
